Harris, in short, is still a narrow favorite in the polls over Donald Trump=
=2E But it=E2=80=99s clear
from the data=E2=80=94and certain strategic decisions=E2=80=94that Harris h=
as lost the mega-momentum that carried her through the summer and is now st=
ruggling to seal the deal in those core battleground states, Pennsylvania c=
hief among them, that would get her to 270. As one Republican media consult=
ant working on House races texted me the other day about Kamala-mentum: =E2=
=80=9CThe new car smell has worn off.=E2=80=9D

The Harris campaign is leading with women voters by a wider margin than Tru=
mp leads with men, and the gender gap may end up pulling Harris over the fi=
nish line in three weeks. But Wilmington is currently playing a game of dem=
ographic whack-a-mole to shore up the weak spots in her theoretical coaliti=
on: Hispanics, Black men, and men under the age of 30 of any race. On Monda=
y, Harris rolled out a slate of plans aimed at Black men=E2=80=94small busi=
ness loans, training and mentorship programs, a new healthcare initiative=
=E2=80=94an agenda she discussed earlier today on The Shade
Room and Unfiltered With Roland Martin. Harris is also doing a town hall in=
 Detroit on Tuesday with Charlamagne tha God, the outspoken co-host of The =
Breakfast Club.

We=E2=80=99ll see if Charlamagne mentions his current beef with Barack Obam=
a, who, in a rare messaging flub, went out of his way to scold Black men in=
 Pittsburgh last week, claiming they=E2=80=99re afraid to support Harris be=
cause she=E2=80=99s a woman. =E2=80=8B=E2=80=8B=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m speakin=
g to men directly,=E2=80=9D Obama said. =E2=80=9CPart of it makes me think =
that, well, you just aren=E2=80=99t feeling the idea of having a woman as p=
resident, and you=E2=80=99re coming up with other alternatives and other re=
asons for that.=E2=80=9D It was a rare whiff for Obama, suggesting his impe=
ccable political antennae might be a little rusty. Maybe, just maybe, there=
 could be other reasons Black men aren=E2=80=99t hyped about the Democratic=
 ticket? On his radio show Monday, Charlamagne called Obama=E2=80=99s claim=
 =E2=80=9Cwhack=E2=80=9D and
=E2=80=9Cnonsense,=E2=80=9D saying =E2=80=9Cthere is a disdain for the enti=
re Democratic Party, and it=E2=80=99s not specific to the vice president. B=
lack men want to know what to expect from a Harris and Walz administration!=
=E2=80=9D

That=E2=80=99s a sentiment I heard last week, too, while I was on a reporti=
ng swing through Georgia, South Carolina, and North Carolina, talking to Ge=
n Z voters on campuses about the election. I was on a college tour for my S=
napchat show, Good Luck America, interviewing Black voters at UNC-Charlotte=
, progressive women at the Savannah College of Art and Design (SCAD), and T=
rump supporters at Clemson University. It was good to be out on the road, t=
alking to normies about the election, because it let me pressure test the d=
oom-and-gloom headlines about the Harris campaign that have been ricochetin=
g around Twitter in recent days. Yes, my conversations were only with voter=
s under the age of 30 on college campuses=E2=80=94not exactly representativ=
e of the national electorate.
But Gen Z, as I=E2=80=99ve been writing all year, could be pivotal come Nov=
ember. Young women are flocking to Harris in historic numbers, while young =
men are moving away from the Democratic Party and toward Trump. It=E2=80=99=
s still an open question whether Harris will win enough young voters to win=
 the election.

So, here=E2=80=99s what I gleaned from interviews with about 50 young voter=
s on college campuses, many of whom said they are voting in their first ele=
ction: First, the momentum for Harris has stalled, but not in a way that=E2=
=80=99s fatal for her campaign. As one student at SCAD told me, a young wom=
an named Zoe who is voting for Harris: =E2=80=9CBrat summer is definitely o=
ver. People have calmed down and they=E2=80=99re digging into the issues.=
=E2=80=9D

Second, the people I spoke with want Harris to explain in more detail what =
she would do differently than Joe Biden, who, in their young minds, is most=
ly responsible for the high cost of living and the two overseas wars
that began during his presidency. And finally, there was an openness to Tru=
mp, even among students who say they are voting for Harris, on the issues o=
f the economy and prices. Sure, some students considered Trump evil, a nons=
tarter, a chaos agent, an existential threat to their identities. But other=
s, even Democrats, just thought of him as the Republican choice on the ball=
ot, and someone who might be better on the economy than Harris.

Sure, maybe Obama is onto something. Harris might be facing skepticism beca=
use of her race and gender, biases that aren=E2=80=99t exactly brought up p=
roactively in interviews with reporters. But in my conversations with Gen Z=
 voters of all stripes=E2=80=94men, women, Democrat, Republican, Black, whi=
te, Latino, and Asian=E2=80=94Harris=E2=80=99s biggest challenge right now =
is trust. Even among voters who said they were going to vote for Harris, fe=
w could articulate what she stood for beyond protecting abortion rights. He=
re are some notes on how
these conversations went on each campus I visited.

