The Young Progressives

Zoe, who is from Virginia but declined to share her last name, was happy to=
 vote for Harris, but said she wasn=E2=80=99t as hyped as some of her frien=
ds and classmates. She said the blizzard of TikToks and slime edits that bu=
oyed Harris on social media over the summer were akin to =E2=80=9Cpropagand=
a=E2=80=9D that got young people excited about the campaign=E2=80=94not a b=
ad thing=E2=80=94but have since become a little cringe. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=
=99s all people were talking about, the propaganda,=E2=80=9D Zoe said. =E2=
=80=9CLike, we can see you=E2=80=99re just trying to get us to vote for her=
=2E Hopefully, people make the right ch=
oice for whatever they believe in. Som=
e people are still really excited about it, but I haven=E2=80=99t seen as m=
uch excitement recently.=E2=80=9D

Like all of the students I spoke to at SCAD, a private arts school, Zoe was=
 a young progressive woman. Outside the SCAD Museum of Art, where
students were walking to and from classes, I saw a lot of blue hair, tattoo=
s, piercings, and ripped baggy jeans. About half of the students said they =
had registered to vote in Georgia, while others were registered in Pennsylv=
ania, Virginia, Texas, or North Carolina=E2=80=94all states with competitiv=
e statewide races on the ballot this fall. =E2=80=9CI know it=E2=80=99s not=
 supposed to be a reason you vote for someone, but it does excite me that s=
he=E2=80=99s a woman,=E2=80=9D said Riley Alexander, a junior at the colleg=
e. =E2=80=9CI think that=E2=80=99s going to be really exciting and empoweri=
ng for a lot of girls out there. But also, just in comparison to Biden, she=
=E2=80=99s younger, she=E2=80=99s more passionate. I can listen to her with=
out falling asleep.=E2=80=9D Another student named Ella told me she would h=
ave been =E2=80=9Chorrified=E2=80=9D to vote for Biden because of his age, =
but she=E2=80=99s glad Harris has stepped in. When I asked Ella if she want=
ed Harris to break with Biden on certain issues, or outline a different
agenda, she said it didn=E2=80=99t really matter. =E2=80=9CShe=E2=80=99s no=
t an old white man,=E2=80=9D she told me. =E2=80=9CShe=E2=80=99s not senile=
=2E=E2=80=9D

All of the SCAD students called themselves progressive. Most of the women w=
ere white, two were Black. Their top issues were climate change, gun violen=
ce, abortion, and LGBTQ rights. Several identified as queer or nonbinary, a=
nd said they worried about their safety and dating lives under a Trump admi=
nistration. Almost none of them talked about prices or the economy. Four of=
 them went out of their way to express concerns about Israel=E2=80=99s ongo=
ing war in Gaza, even as the issue seems to have faded from the campaign he=
adlines since Harris joined the race. Julia Bennet, a sophomore from Cheste=
r, Pennsylvania, said she was planning to vote third party, or not vote at =
all, when Biden was the nominee, in part because of the war. =E2=80=9CI kin=
d of wasn=E2=80=99t thinking of voting with Biden,=E2=80=9D she told me. =
=E2=80=9CI was even thinking of voting for a third
party, just because he didn=E2=80=99t really seem with it.=E2=80=9D When I =
asked Julia if she thought Harris would do anything differently on Gaza, sh=
e couldn=E2=80=99t say. She was just excited to vote for Harris =E2=80=94 b=
ut wanted her to stand up to Israel more than Biden. =E2=80=9CI just hope s=
he takes more action on the genocide,=E2=80=9D she told me.

The Trump Bros

After leaving Savannah, my film crew and I drove up to Clemson University, =
just in time for some crisp fall weather in the foothills. Yeah, I know Sou=
th Carolina isn=E2=80=99t a battleground state like Georgia. But Clemson is=
 a Republican-leaning campus, and given the attention being lavished on the=
 =E2=80=9CBro Vote=E2=80=9D by reporters in recent months, I wanted to get =
inside the minds of young men who are planning to vote for Trump.

My biggest takeaway on campus is that support for Trump isn=E2=80=99t just =
about Zyn or Joe Rogan or the UFC celebrities who have gone MAGA. Some cult=
ure war topics came up. One dude named Reaves, who was wearing Croakies and=
 said he loves to hunt and fish, told me he supports Trump because of =E2=
=80=9Cguns.=E2=80=9D Another student, James Regan, argued that =E2=80=9Cyou=
ng men are going to the right just because
of how active and woke the far left has gotten. I think it kind of annoys t=
hem a little bit.=E2=80=9D But Regan, and most of the Clemson students I sp=
oke to, weren=E2=80=99t buffoonish caricatures plucked out of the manospher=
e, parroting the Nelk Boys or complaining about pronoun culture. They had g=
ood reasons to support Trump, and they understood, too, why young women wer=
e backing Harris.

I talked to mostly white men on campus. Several talked about how they thoug=
ht Trump was =E2=80=9Cstrong=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Ca fighter,=E2=80=9D with=
 a few referencing that now-famous photo of a bloody and defiant Trump rais=
ing his fist after a shooter nearly took his life in Butler, Pennsylvania, =
over the summer. But none of these men talked about Harris with the sexism =
or contempt I heard from young Trump supporters about Hillary Clinton back =
in 2016. =E2=80=9CShe=E2=80=99s a really good speaker and I understand her =
appeal,=E2=80=9D said a student named Anthony Colella. =E2=80=9CShe is real=
ly optimistic. We saw it
in the debate. She knows how to rally people behind her. But my issue is, w=
e don=E2=80=99t know exactly what she wants. What is her plan? I=E2=80=99m =
not sure. I kind of think it=E2=80=99s like, =E2=80=98High on vibes, low on=
 substance.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D

Like Anthony, several other young men went out of their way to offer qualif=
ied praise of Harris=E2=80=99s personal attributes and political talents, i=
n particular her debate performance against Trump. It was a small counterpo=
int to the claim Obama made in Pittsburgh, that young male voters are outri=
ght contemptuous of a woman in politics. =E2=80=9CIn that debate, she shock=
ed me a little bit,=E2=80=9D said Geoffrey Hunt, a freshman pounding a Cels=
ius on his way to a marketing class. =E2=80=9CI really do try to have an un=
biased opinion, and she did a lot better than I thought that she was going =
to do. I was watching and looking at how she carries herself. She has this =
homey, good, welcoming feeling about her. I just don=E2=80=99t think any of=
 her policies or anything
she=E2=80=99s done necessarily supports that.=E2=80=9D

These young men also said they understood the growing gender gap inside Gen=
 Z, and several said they sympathized with young women moving to Harris bec=
ause of her loud and proud support for abortion rights. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=
=99s pretty clear that what=E2=80=99s pulling women left is her stance on a=
bortion, and I totally get that,=E2=80=9D Regan told me. =E2=80=9CAs a man,=
 abortion doesn=E2=80=99t have as much to do with me as it does women.=E2=
=80=9D

But most of the Clemson students cited one of two main reasons for supporti=
ng Trump: They were either socially conservative pro-lifers, or they figure=
d Trump would do a better job bringing down the cost of living and managing=
 the economy. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m not alone in thinking that this election=
 is a pick of necessary evils,=E2=80=9D said Will Lawson, a junior from Ape=
x, North Carolina. =E2=80=9CI mean, you don=E2=80=99t love all of Trump's r=
hetoric, but I also understand that he=E2=80=99s needed for this country. I=
 don=E2=80=99t
understand how you can look at the past four years and understand that Kama=
la Harris has been the vice president, she=E2=80=99s part of this administr=
ation, and the very simple point that=E2=80=99s just compelling to me is li=
ke, Do I want four more years of this? And for me, that=E2=80=99s no. Groce=
ry prices were down. Gas prices going down. Immigrants are coming over the =
border. It just feels like the Democratic Party isn=E2=80=99t looking out f=
or me as a citizen.=E2=80=9D

