Young Black Voters

After Clemson, we hit the road again, driving on I-85 past the glorious Gaf=
fney Peachoid ( https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peachoid?utm_campaign=3DThe+B=
est+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2810%2F14%2F24%29&utm_content=3DThe+Be=
st+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2810%2F1%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_act=
ion&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) on our way to =
UNC-Charlotte. It=E2=80=99s one of North Carolina=E2=80=99s largest public =
universities, with a student body of about 30,000. They=E2=80=99re mostly r=
esidents of the swing state, and the school also happens to be about 40 per=
cent nonwhite. It was there that I encountered the real-world version of so=
me of the narratives we=E2=80=99ve been seeing play out this week with the =
Harris campaign and Black voters.

When we arrived, it was the final day to register to vote in North Carolina=
=2E Different groups were tabling all o=
ver campus, signing up voters, many of=
 them
as young as 18, voting in their very first presidential election. The women=
 at Charlotte? They were absolutely fired up and ready to vote for Harris, =
whether they were Black, white, or Latino. =E2=80=9CI am so excited to vote=
,=E2=80=9D said Sameeah Booker, an 18-year-old freshman. =E2=80=9CShe suppo=
rts me. She cares more about women like me. Like, I=E2=80=99m a Black femal=
e living in America. Trump wants to take away a lot of the stuff that=E2=80=
=99s kind of helping everybody right now. And he=E2=80=99s not understandin=
g a lot of the different viewpoints of other people. He=E2=80=99s really ra=
cist, too.=E2=80=9D

Booker laughed when I asked her to name the first thing that came to mind w=
hen I mentioned Trump=E2=80=99s name. =E2=80=9CHe=E2=80=99s eating the dogs=
, he=E2=80=99s eating the cats,=E2=80=9D she said, reciting the TikTok remi=
x of Trump=E2=80=99s bogus debate rant about the Haitians in Springfield, O=
hio. I played that word association game with other students, asking them t=
o name a word or phrase when I mentioned each
candidate. Among the words they mentioned for Trump: orange, racist, rude, =
close-minded, disgusting, Project 2025. One student, Natalie Martinez, just=
 responded: =E2=80=9CEwwww.=E2=80=9D

But several male students at Charlotte=E2=80=94all Black, all leaning Harri=
s=E2=80=94also named =E2=80=9Cbusiness=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cbusinessman=E2=
=80=9D when I asked them the question about Trump. Or they called him =E2=
=80=9Cfunny.=E2=80=9D When I asked those same men to name a word about Harr=
is, they said things like =E2=80=9Cunsure,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Ctrust,=E2=80=
=9D and =E2=80=9Cconfused.=E2=80=9D It became clear that while these younge=
r Black men were probably going to vote for Harris, they didn=E2=80=99t har=
bor the same reflexive anger or hate toward Trump that their female classma=
tes did. =E2=80=9CShe=E2=80=99s got a great background,=E2=80=9D said Tsadi=
q Jones, a freshman from the Raleigh area. =E2=80=9CI saw she worked at McD=
onald=E2=80=99s. But at the same time, I want to know, is she actually goin=
g to do what=E2=80=99s better for the economy? What=E2=80=99s different fro=
m Biden?
Because Donald Trump is a businessman, so he knows, especially from a monet=
ary perspective, how to shift the economy in a way that it=E2=80=99s better=
 for people, especially when buying gas and this and that.=E2=80=9D

Jones, like the other students I spoke with in Charlotte, said he was proba=
bly going to vote for Harris. But I got the sense as I chatted with him, an=
d the other young male voters on campus, that he could easily change his mi=
nd at the last second before casting his ballot. To him, Trump simply isn=
=E2=80=99t the evil bogeyman that older Democrats think he is. After all, J=
ones=E2=80=94now voting in his first election=E2=80=94was only 9 years old =
when Trump came down that escalator back in 2015. He doesn=E2=80=99t rememb=
er the madness. But he does worry about the future.

