248" style=3D"color:#d40000;text-decoration:none;font-weight:bold" class=3D=
"sdf">here</a></u> if you missed it. <br/><br/>Harris, in short, is still a=
 narrow favorite in the polls over <b>Donald</b> <b>Trump</b>. But it=E2=80=
=99s clear
from the data=E2=80=94and certain strategic decisions=E2=80=94that Harris h=
as lost the mega-momentum that carried her through the summer and is now st=
ruggling to seal the deal in those core battleground states, Pennsylvania c=
hief among them, that would get her to 270. As one Republican media consult=
ant working on House races texted me the other day about Kamala-mentum: =E2=
=80=9CThe new car smell has worn off.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>The Harris campaign=
 is leading with women voters by a wider margin than Trump leads with men, =
and the gender gap may end up pulling Harris over the finish line in three =
weeks. But Wilmington is currently playing a game of demographic whack-a-mo=
le to shore up the weak spots in her theoretical coalition: Hispanics, Blac=
k men, and men under the age of 30 of <i>any</i> race. On Monday, Harris ro=
lled out a slate of plans aimed at Black men=E2=80=94small business loans, =
training and mentorship programs, a new healthcare initiative=E2=80=94an ag=
enda she discussed earlier today on <i>The Shade
Room</i> and <i>Unfiltered With Roland Martin</i>. Harris is also doing a t=
own hall in Detroit on Tuesday with <b>Charlamagne tha God</b>, the outspok=
en co-host of <i>The Breakfast Club</i>. <br/><br/>We=E2=80=99ll see if Cha=
rlamagne mentions his current beef with <b>Barack</b> <b>Obama</b>, who, in=
 a rare messaging flub, went out of his way to scold Black men in Pittsburg=
h last week, claiming they=E2=80=99re afraid to support Harris because she=
=E2=80=99s a woman. =E2=80=8B=E2=80=8B=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m speaking to men =
directly,=E2=80=9D Obama said. =E2=80=9CPart of it makes me think that, wel=
l, you just aren=E2=80=99t feeling the idea of having a woman as president,=
 and you=E2=80=99re coming up with other alternatives and other reasons for=
 that.=E2=80=9D It was a rare whiff for Obama, suggesting his impeccable po=
litical antennae might be a little rusty. Maybe, just <i>maybe</i>, there c=
ould be other reasons Black men aren=E2=80=99t hyped about the Democratic t=
icket? On his radio show Monday, Charlamagne called Obama=E2=80=99s claim =
=E2=80=9Cwhack=E2=80=9D and
=E2=80=9Cnonsense,=E2=80=9D saying =E2=80=9Cthere is a disdain for the enti=
re Democratic Party, and it=E2=80=99s not specific to the vice president. B=
lack men want to know what to expect from a Harris and Walz administration!=
=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>That=E2=80=99s a sentiment I heard last week, too, while=
 I was on a reporting swing through Georgia, South Carolina, and North Caro=
lina, talking to Gen Z voters on campuses about the election. I was on a co=
llege tour for my Snapchat show, <i>Good Luck America</i>, interviewing Bla=
ck voters at UNC-Charlotte, progressive women at the Savannah College of Ar=
t and Design (SCAD), and Trump supporters at Clemson University. It was goo=
d to be out on the road, talking to normies about the election, because it =
let me pressure test the doom-and-gloom headlines about the Harris campaign=
 that have been ricocheting around Twitter in recent days. Yes, my conversa=
tions were only with voters under the age of 30 on college campuses=E2=80=
=94not exactly representative of the national electorate.
But Gen Z, as I=E2=80=99ve been writing all year, could be pivotal come Nov=
ember. Young women are flocking to Harris in historic numbers, while young =
men are moving away from the Democratic Party and toward Trump. It=E2=80=99=
s still an open question whether Harris will win enough young voters to win=
 the election.<br/><br/>So, here=E2=80=99s what I gleaned from interviews w=
ith about 50 young voters on college campuses, many of whom said they are v=
oting in their first election: First, the momentum for Harris has stalled, =
but not in a way that=E2=80=99s fatal for her campaign. As one student at S=
CAD told me, a young woman named <b>Zoe</b> who is voting for Harris: =E2=
=80=9CBrat summer is definitely over. People have calmed down and they=E2=
=80=99re digging into the issues.=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>Second, the people I s=
poke with want Harris to explain in more detail what she would do different=
ly than <b>Joe</b> <b>Biden</b>, who, in their young minds, is mostly respo=
nsible for the high cost of living and the two overseas wars
that began during his presidency. And finally, there was an openness to Tru=
mp, even among students who say they are voting for Harris, on the issues o=
f the economy and prices. Sure, some students considered Trump evil, a nons=
tarter, a chaos agent, an existential threat to their identities. But other=
s, even Democrats, just thought of him as the Republican choice on the ball=
ot, and someone who might be better on the economy than Harris.<br/><br/>Su=
re, maybe Obama is onto something. Harris <i>might</i> be facing skepticism=
 because of her race and gender, biases that aren=E2=80=99t exactly brought=
 up proactively in interviews with reporters. But in my conversations with =
Gen Z voters of all stripes=E2=80=94men, women, Democrat, Republican, Black=
, white, Latino, and Asian=E2=80=94Harris=E2=80=99s biggest challenge right=
 now is <i>trust</i>. Even among voters who said they were going to vote fo=
r Harris, few could articulate what she stood for beyond protecting abortio=
n rights. Here are some notes on how
these conversations went on each campus I visited.<br/></td>
