x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Zoe, who is from Vi=
rginia but declined to share her last name, was happy to vote for Harris, b=
ut said she wasn=E2=80=99t as hyped as some of her friends and classmates. =
She said the blizzard of TikToks and slime edits that buoyed Harris on soci=
al media over the summer were akin to =E2=80=9Cpropaganda=E2=80=9D that got=
 young people excited about the campaign=E2=80=94not a bad thing=E2=80=94bu=
t have since become a little cringe. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s all people were =
talking about, the propaganda,=E2=80=9D Zoe said. =E2=80=9CLike, we can see=
 you=E2=80=99re just trying to get us to vote for her. Hopefully, people ma=
ke the right choice for whatever they believe in. Some people are still rea=
lly excited about it, but I haven=E2=80=99t seen as much excitement recentl=
y.=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>Like all of the students I spoke to at SCAD, a privat=
e arts school, Zoe was a young progressive woman. Outside the SCAD Museum o=
f Art, where
students were walking to and from classes, I saw a lot of blue hair, tattoo=
s, piercings, and ripped baggy jeans. About half of the students said they =
had registered to vote in Georgia, while others were registered in Pennsylv=
ania, Virginia, Texas, or North Carolina=E2=80=94all states with competitiv=
e statewide races on the ballot this fall. =E2=80=9CI know it=E2=80=99s not=
 supposed to be a reason you vote for someone, but it does excite me that s=
he=E2=80=99s a woman,=E2=80=9D said <b>Riley</b> <b>Alexander</b>, a junior=
 at the college. =E2=80=9CI think that=E2=80=99s going to be really excitin=
g and empowering for a lot of girls out there. But also, just in comparison=
 to Biden, she=E2=80=99s younger, she=E2=80=99s more passionate. I can list=
en to her without falling asleep.=E2=80=9D Another student named <b>Ella</b=
> told me she would have been =E2=80=9Chorrified=E2=80=9D to vote for Biden=
 because of his age, but she=E2=80=99s glad Harris has stepped in. When I a=
sked Ella if she wanted Harris to break with Biden on certain issues, or ou=
tline a different
agenda, she said it didn=E2=80=99t really matter.  =E2=80=9CShe=E2=80=99s n=
ot an old white man,=E2=80=9D she told me. =E2=80=9CShe=E2=80=99s not senil=
e.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>All of the SCAD students called themselves progressive=
=2E Most of the women were white, two w=
ere Black. Their top issues were clima=
te change, gun violence, abortion, and LGBTQ rights. Several identified as =
queer or nonbinary, and said they worried about their safety and dating liv=
es under a Trump administration. Almost none of them talked about prices or=
 the economy. Four of them went out of their way to express concerns about =
Israel=E2=80=99s ongoing war in Gaza, even as the issue seems to have faded=
 from the campaign headlines since Harris joined the race. <b>Julia</b> <b>=
Bennet</b>, a sophomore from Chester, Pennsylvania, said she was planning t=
o vote third party, or not vote at all, when Biden was the nominee, in part=
 because of the war. =E2=80=9CI kind of wasn=E2=80=99t thinking of voting w=
ith Biden,=E2=80=9D she told me. =E2=80=9CI was even thinking of voting for=
 a third
party, just because he didn=E2=80=99t really seem with it.=E2=80=9D When I =
asked Julia if she thought Harris would do anything differently on Gaza, sh=
e couldn=E2=80=99t say. She was just excited to vote for Harris =E2=80=94 b=
ut wanted her to stand up to Israel more than Biden. =E2=80=9CI just hope s=
he takes more action on the genocide,=E2=80=9D she told me.<br/></td>
