x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">After Clemson, we h=
it the road again, driving on I-85 past the glorious <u><a href=3D"https://=
email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dTamdNcjZoajF=
XUm1GSUd5eEQ2OD0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvUGVhY2=
hvaWQ_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPVRoZStCZXN0KyUyNitUaGUrQnJpZ2h0ZXN0Ky0rU1VCU0NSSUJFU=
lMrJTI4MTAlMkYxNCUyRjI0JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX2NvbnRlbnQ9VGhlK0Jlc3QrJTI2K1RoZStC=
cmlnaHRlc3QrLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjgxMCUyRjElMkYyNCUyOVx1MDAyNnV0bV9tZWRpdW0=
9ZW1haWxfYWN0aW9uXHUwMDI2dXRtX3NvdXJjZT1jdXN0b21lci5pb1x1MDAyNnV0bV90ZXJtPW=
Y2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImludGVybmFsIjoiZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwibGlua=
19pZCI6MTEzNjYxMX0/781b1418e4b9b68b919213a6293cf6b70f61ed7830e24d09b25a4b86=
c9e943ee" style=3D"color:#d40000;text-decoration:none;font-weight:bold" cla=
ss=3D"sdf">Gaffney Peachoid</a></u> on our way to UNC-Charlotte. It=E2=80=
=99s one of North Carolina=E2=80=99s largest public universities, with a st=
udent body of about 30,000. They=E2=80=99re mostly residents of the swing s=
tate, and the school also happens to be about 40 percent nonwhite. It was t=
here that I encountered the real-world version of some of the narratives we=
=E2=80=99ve been seeing play out this week with the Harris campaign and Bla=
ck voters.<br/><br/>When we arrived, it was the final day to register to vo=
te in North Carolina. Different groups were tabling all over campus, signin=
g up voters, many of them
as young as 18, voting in their very first presidential election. The women=
 at Charlotte? They were absolutely fired up and ready to vote for Harris, =
whether they were Black, white, or Latino. =E2=80=9CI am so excited to vote=
,=E2=80=9D said <b>Sameeah</b> <b>Booker</b>, an 18-year-old freshman. =E2=
=80=9CShe supports me. She cares more about women like me. Like, I=E2=80=99=
m a Black female living in America. Trump wants to take away a lot of the s=
tuff that=E2=80=99s kind of helping everybody right now. And he=E2=80=99s n=
ot understanding a lot of the different viewpoints of other people. He=E2=
=80=99s really racist, too.=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>Booker laughed when I asked =
her to name the first thing that came to mind when I mentioned Trump=E2=80=
=99s name. =E2=80=9CHe=E2=80=99s eating the dogs, he=E2=80=99s eating the c=
ats,=E2=80=9D she said, reciting the TikTok remix of Trump=E2=80=99s bogus =
debate rant about the Haitians in Springfield, Ohio. I played that word ass=
ociation game with other students, asking them to name a word or phrase whe=
n I mentioned each
candidate. Among the words they mentioned for Trump: orange, racist, rude, =
close-minded, disgusting, Project 2025. One student, <b>Natalie</b> <b>Mart=
inez</b>, just responded: =E2=80=9CEwwww.=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>But several ma=
le students at Charlotte=E2=80=94all Black, all leaning Harris=E2=80=94also=
 named =E2=80=9Cbusiness=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cbusinessman=E2=80=9D when I =
asked them the question about Trump. Or they called him =E2=80=9Cfunny.=E2=
=80=9D When I asked those same men to name a word about Harris, they said t=
hings like =E2=80=9Cunsure,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Ctrust,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9C=
confused.=E2=80=9D It became clear that while these younger Black men were =
probably going to vote for Harris, they didn=E2=80=99t harbor the same refl=
exive anger or hate toward Trump that their female classmates did. =E2=80=
=9CShe=E2=80=99s got a great background,=E2=80=9D said <b>Tsadiq</b> <b>Jon=
es</b>, a freshman from the Raleigh area. =E2=80=9CI saw she worked at McDo=
nald=E2=80=99s. But at the same time, I want to know, is she actually going=
 to do what=E2=80=99s better for the economy? What=E2=80=99s different from=
 Biden?
Because Donald Trump is a businessman, so he knows, especially from a monet=
ary perspective, how to shift the economy in a way that it=E2=80=99s better=
 for people, especially when buying gas and this and that.=E2=80=9D <br/><b=
r/>Jones, like the other students I spoke with in Charlotte, said he was pr=
obably going to vote for Harris. But I got the sense as I chatted with him,=
 and the other young male voters on campus, that he could easily change his=
 mind at the last second before casting his ballot. To him, Trump simply is=
n=E2=80=99t the evil bogeyman that older Democrats think he is. After all, =
Jones=E2=80=94now voting in his first election=E2=80=94was only <i>9 years =
old</i> when Trump came down that escalator back in 2015. He doesn=E2=80=99=
t remember the madness. But he does worry about the future. <br/></td>
